WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.460 --> 00:00:06.980
RICK KLEFFEL: Ladies and
gentlemen, we are privileged

00:00:06.980 --> 00:00:11.200
to have a man who has a habit
of seeing the future of

00:00:11.200 --> 00:00:14.330
America, writing a book about
it, and telling us where we're

00:00:14.330 --> 00:00:17.340
going to be in about five years,
when we don't know it's

00:00:17.340 --> 00:00:19.500
already happened.

00:00:19.500 --> 00:00:20.740
He did so--

00:00:20.740 --> 00:00:21.860
god--

00:00:21.860 --> 00:00:25.760
longer ago than I would care to
admit, when he gave us all

00:00:25.760 --> 00:00:28.780
"The Electric Kool-Aid Acid
Test." He did it again when he

00:00:28.780 --> 00:00:34.080
told us just what was "The Right
Stuff." He did it again,

00:00:34.080 --> 00:00:36.490
when he said, "I Am Charlotte
Simmons."

00:00:36.490 --> 00:00:38.140
Now he's back again.

00:00:38.140 --> 00:00:40.440
He's one of America's
best authors.

00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:43.010
He's a man who has seen the
future and the present.

00:00:43.010 --> 00:00:44.310
It's Tom Wolfe.

00:00:44.310 --> 00:00:46.350
His new book is "Back
to Blood." Thank you

00:00:46.350 --> 00:00:47.460
for joining me, Tom.

00:00:47.460 --> 00:00:48.710
TOM WOLFE: You're welcome.

00:00:53.140 --> 00:00:55.250
And if you'd really like to see
a vision of the future, go

00:00:55.250 --> 00:00:56.630
to my website.

00:00:56.630 --> 00:00:59.840
It's called Analog.

00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:04.580
You'll have radios again that
you can adjust the volume by

00:01:04.580 --> 00:01:06.310
just turning.

00:01:06.310 --> 00:01:07.600
Didn't anybody ever
see that before?

00:01:07.600 --> 00:01:08.850
You turn a wheel.

00:01:11.210 --> 00:01:12.510
It's very handy.

00:01:12.510 --> 00:01:14.220
But I'm not going to--

00:01:14.220 --> 00:01:18.210
I have a feeling it
may not even go.

00:01:18.210 --> 00:01:20.490
RICK KLEFFEL: One of the things
that struck me as I

00:01:20.490 --> 00:01:26.190
read this book was that, in
fact, this is something you do

00:01:26.190 --> 00:01:27.530
have a habit of doing.

00:01:27.530 --> 00:01:32.920
Is finding out what America's
really about, and going there,

00:01:32.920 --> 00:01:35.000
and telling us two
stories at once.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:39.650
How America got that way, in the
midst of a thrilling story

00:01:39.650 --> 00:01:42.060
about characters we
really care about.

00:01:42.060 --> 00:01:45.630
And I'm wondering, what took you
to Miami to show us this

00:01:45.630 --> 00:01:48.820
particular vision of America?

00:01:48.820 --> 00:01:51.880
TOM WOLFE: I was really
interested in immigration.

00:01:51.880 --> 00:01:54.780
And this was at a time when
most of the immigration

00:01:54.780 --> 00:01:56.720
stories-- and sometimes they
were great stories-- about how

00:01:56.720 --> 00:01:59.585
people got in to the
United States.

00:01:59.585 --> 00:02:01.460
But that had been
done to death.

00:02:01.460 --> 00:02:03.250
And I was curious about
what did immigrants do

00:02:03.250 --> 00:02:04.790
once they were here.

00:02:04.790 --> 00:02:09.280
And I was first interested in
the Vietnamese in California,

00:02:09.280 --> 00:02:14.000
who, for the most part, I guess,
are still in the Los

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:14.760
Angeles region.

00:02:14.760 --> 00:02:20.630
But I then saw that the San
Jose Mercury, which is

00:02:20.630 --> 00:02:24.130
northern California, has a
second edition, which is

00:02:24.130 --> 00:02:27.370
called the Viet Mercury.

00:02:27.370 --> 00:02:29.690
I really would like to get
to know the Vietnamese.

00:02:29.690 --> 00:02:32.460
Then I discovered I can't speak
the language, and I

00:02:32.460 --> 00:02:35.360
can't even begin to read
the Viet Mercury.

00:02:39.150 --> 00:02:41.030
But I was interested
in immigration.

00:02:41.030 --> 00:02:43.270
And people say, what are
you interested in now?

00:02:43.270 --> 00:02:45.580
And I'd say, well, I'm
interested in immigration.

00:02:45.580 --> 00:02:47.180
And they'd say, oh
that's great.

00:02:47.180 --> 00:02:50.230
And then their heads
would fall off.

00:02:50.230 --> 00:02:54.110
They'd go to sleep like
a horse, standing up.

00:02:54.110 --> 00:02:56.900
But I had faith in
that subject.

00:02:56.900 --> 00:02:59.500
And then I heard about Miami.

00:02:59.500 --> 00:03:01.990
Of course, I'd heard of Miami
before, but not in connection

00:03:01.990 --> 00:03:05.810
to immigration.

00:03:05.810 --> 00:03:11.870
Miami is really immigration
central for the United States.

00:03:11.870 --> 00:03:13.680
It's the only city--

00:03:13.680 --> 00:03:16.360
I think it's the only city in
the world, as far as I know--

00:03:16.360 --> 00:03:20.430
in which more than half the
population is recent

00:03:20.430 --> 00:03:23.390
immigrants, many within
the last 50 years.

00:03:23.390 --> 00:03:27.350
And people from another
country, with another

00:03:27.350 --> 00:03:33.570
language, and another culture
politically, control this vast

00:03:33.570 --> 00:03:37.280
metropolitan area of Miami.

00:03:37.280 --> 00:03:39.630
Of course, I'm talking
about the Cubans.

00:03:39.630 --> 00:03:45.640
It's interesting, just
how unusual that is.

00:03:45.640 --> 00:03:48.810
Russians are coming in in
great numbers right now.

00:03:48.810 --> 00:03:53.750
And they tend to live where
Miami Beach joins the

00:03:53.750 --> 00:03:58.470
mainland, north of
South Beach.

00:03:58.470 --> 00:04:00.210
I consider this book
are great triumph.

00:04:00.210 --> 00:04:03.770
It hardly mentions South
Beach at all.

00:04:03.770 --> 00:04:08.560
Very few contemporary books
on Miami do that.

00:04:08.560 --> 00:04:15.959
And realizing that I really knew
nothing about Miami, I

00:04:15.959 --> 00:04:20.339
still thought it was a tourist
resort, I decided the only way

00:04:20.339 --> 00:04:23.800
to find out just to go there.

00:04:23.800 --> 00:04:25.390
And I had good luck.

00:04:25.390 --> 00:04:30.020
There was a former journalist
for the Miami Herald, a second

00:04:30.020 --> 00:04:33.170
generation Cuban named Oscar
Corral, wrote me out of the

00:04:33.170 --> 00:04:36.010
blue, and said, I think you'll
find it interesting here.

00:04:36.010 --> 00:04:36.960
And so I went.

00:04:36.960 --> 00:04:40.470
And I find if you can
get along with--

00:04:40.470 --> 00:04:45.600
Oscar is great-- but if you can
get along with one person

00:04:45.600 --> 00:04:50.660
for five hours anywhere you go,
that first will probably

00:04:50.660 --> 00:04:52.680
introduce you to
somebody else.

00:04:52.680 --> 00:04:55.210
And it goes from there.

00:04:55.210 --> 00:04:57.470
A, I never tried to report
in a white suit.

00:04:57.470 --> 00:04:58.340
Everbody would say, hey!

00:04:58.340 --> 00:04:58.940
Tom Wolfe is here!

00:04:58.940 --> 00:05:01.490
Talk to me.

00:05:01.490 --> 00:05:03.710
I wear a blue blazer.

00:05:03.710 --> 00:05:06.040
But come to think of it,
I guess I do stand out,

00:05:06.040 --> 00:05:07.020
because I have a--

00:05:07.020 --> 00:05:09.590
anybody here know
what this is?

00:05:09.590 --> 00:05:10.300
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:10.300 --> 00:05:11.680
RICK KLEFFEL: Polka dot tie.

00:05:11.680 --> 00:05:12.930
TOM WOLFE: Right, a tie.

00:05:15.390 --> 00:05:18.360
There are parts of America
where these are unknown.

00:05:18.360 --> 00:05:22.710
I just discovered
them recently.

00:05:22.710 --> 00:05:23.840
And if anybody would like them,

00:05:23.840 --> 00:05:25.875
I'll tell you my supplier.

00:05:25.875 --> 00:05:27.450
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:27.450 --> 00:05:28.130
TOM WOLFE: Anyway.

00:05:28.130 --> 00:05:30.640
RICK KLEFFEL: Now Tom, one of
the things that struck me

00:05:30.640 --> 00:05:33.180
about reading this book, and
thinking of all your other

00:05:33.180 --> 00:05:37.750
books going back, is that before
there was a Google,

00:05:37.750 --> 00:05:41.940
your books were designed to be
read by somebody who has

00:05:41.940 --> 00:05:44.130
Google to hand, to summon up.

00:05:44.130 --> 00:05:45.830
To go, oh my god.

00:05:45.830 --> 00:05:47.890
Could that really be true?

00:05:47.890 --> 00:05:52.620
They're filled with these kind
of details that call out their

00:05:52.620 --> 00:05:54.380
attention to us.

00:05:54.380 --> 00:05:58.400
I'd like to talk about some of
the finding those kind of real

00:05:58.400 --> 00:06:02.670
life details, and putting them
in your fiction, and putting

00:06:02.670 --> 00:06:05.190
them in your nonfiction, and
telling a story with these

00:06:05.190 --> 00:06:06.740
great little bits.

00:06:06.740 --> 00:06:09.930
And also, did you use
Google when you were

00:06:09.930 --> 00:06:10.800
writing this book?

00:06:10.800 --> 00:06:13.820
TOM WOLFE: Oh my god.

00:06:13.820 --> 00:06:19.850
I'm one out of eight billion,
I think, who do use Google.

00:06:19.850 --> 00:06:21.550
Think of all the times
I didn't go

00:06:21.550 --> 00:06:23.660
New York Public library.

00:06:23.660 --> 00:06:25.150
I sat home.

00:06:25.150 --> 00:06:26.665
I have to ask, though,
about Google.

00:06:29.480 --> 00:06:34.970
When I look things up, I've
learned more about ornithology

00:06:34.970 --> 00:06:38.350
by using Google all the time.

00:06:38.350 --> 00:06:40.350
You can always recognize
the dove--

00:06:40.350 --> 00:06:43.500
it's flying through
a commercial--

00:06:43.500 --> 00:06:48.950
it has a staggered flight.

00:06:48.950 --> 00:06:52.160
And even swans taking off.

00:06:52.160 --> 00:06:53.790
I've seen a lot of swans.

00:06:53.790 --> 00:06:57.000
They can take off very,
very rapidly.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:00.460
There are other things to learn,
other than the facts

00:07:00.460 --> 00:07:02.390
that you're looking for.

00:07:02.390 --> 00:07:05.570
And it's very attractive
to see these birds.

00:07:05.570 --> 00:07:08.850
RICK KLEFFEL: So you're one of
the many authors who find

00:07:08.850 --> 00:07:12.170
Google to be something of a
mixed blessing, in that it

00:07:12.170 --> 00:07:12.760
offers you--

00:07:12.760 --> 00:07:12.910
TOM WOLFE: Oh, no.

00:07:12.910 --> 00:07:13.900
It's not mixed it all.

00:07:13.900 --> 00:07:15.700
I learn about other things.

00:07:15.700 --> 00:07:16.170
RICK KLEFFEL: So you--

00:07:16.170 --> 00:07:17.420
TOM WOLFE: Birds.

00:07:19.680 --> 00:07:25.050
Anyway, I'm not comfortable
with something I'm writing

00:07:25.050 --> 00:07:26.920
about, even in a novel.

00:07:26.920 --> 00:07:30.760
Until I was 57 years old, I
wrote nothing but nonfiction.

00:07:30.760 --> 00:07:34.930
So I paid my dues in
nonfiction work.

00:07:34.930 --> 00:07:37.050
And it was fun, because at
that time, things were

00:07:37.050 --> 00:07:41.180
happening in nonfiction that
hadn't happened before.

00:07:41.180 --> 00:07:43.000
I still think, probably the--

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:44.250
I shouldn't say this.

00:07:47.050 --> 00:07:48.270
Here's the way you
get around it.

00:07:48.270 --> 00:07:50.670
You really want to praise
somebody highly, you say, he's

00:07:50.670 --> 00:07:52.420
one of the two.

00:07:52.420 --> 00:07:57.000
Then all the other writers can
say, oh yeah, I was the other.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:01.370
Anyway, I think Michael Lewis,
who's a nonfiction writer, is

00:08:01.370 --> 00:08:06.614
one of the two greatest writers
in America today.

00:08:06.614 --> 00:08:10.360
I'm not saying that for
my own benefit.

00:08:10.360 --> 00:08:11.000
He's fabulous.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:14.850
He knows how to tell a
story in nonfiction.

00:08:14.850 --> 00:08:17.820
Which is actually not
all that hard.

00:08:17.820 --> 00:08:22.200
There are just four devices that
can make nonfiction sound

00:08:22.200 --> 00:08:26.200
like the most gripping novel
you've ever read.

00:08:26.200 --> 00:08:29.360
One is scene-by-scene
construction.

00:08:29.360 --> 00:08:33.880
So instead of going from a scene
to some long essay about

00:08:33.880 --> 00:08:36.900
something or other, you go to
another scene, and another

00:08:36.900 --> 00:08:38.150
scene, and another scene.

00:08:41.890 --> 00:08:46.370
The second is extensive
dialogue.

00:08:46.370 --> 00:08:48.670
You can't always get that.

00:08:48.670 --> 00:08:51.300
When I wrote a book on
astronauts, I really wasn't

00:08:51.300 --> 00:08:56.320
there when John Glenn made
the first orbital trip.

00:08:56.320 --> 00:08:57.240
But two things helped.

00:08:57.240 --> 00:09:01.810
One, astronauts at that time
had to go through detailed

00:09:01.810 --> 00:09:05.490
question and answer sessions,
because at the time, NASA did

00:09:05.490 --> 00:09:08.750
not know what they were
going to find.

00:09:08.750 --> 00:09:12.170
And I talked them into
declassifying those.

00:09:12.170 --> 00:09:12.750
RICK KLEFFEL: Really?

00:09:12.750 --> 00:09:14.520
TOM WOLFE: Yes.

00:09:14.520 --> 00:09:16.170
They started scratching their
heads, well, I don't know why

00:09:16.170 --> 00:09:17.420
we keep these declassified.

00:09:20.060 --> 00:09:25.490
Also, I use something that I
call the downstage voice.

00:09:25.490 --> 00:09:28.240
If you're really stymied
for accurate--

00:09:28.240 --> 00:09:30.610
and even in writing
a novel, I want

00:09:30.610 --> 00:09:31.860
this stuff to be accurate--

00:09:34.150 --> 00:09:41.710
you could write in the third
person narrative as if you're

00:09:41.710 --> 00:09:47.720
a voice of someone or some
typical character in the book.

00:09:47.720 --> 00:09:50.530
At one point, I was writing
about Junior Johnson, a stock

00:09:50.530 --> 00:09:52.520
car driver.

00:09:52.520 --> 00:09:56.250
And he's in a practice
run around the

00:09:56.250 --> 00:09:59.090
North Wilkesboro Raceway.

00:09:59.090 --> 00:10:03.990
And he was the fastest
driver that was in

00:10:03.990 --> 00:10:05.640
NASCAR at the time.

00:10:05.640 --> 00:10:10.690
And so I suddenly say, "great
smokin' blue gumballs!

00:10:10.690 --> 00:10:13.810
There goes Junior Johnson!"
That was to indicate the

00:10:13.810 --> 00:10:16.610
excitement that he created.

00:10:16.610 --> 00:10:19.570
And it was me speaking.

00:10:19.570 --> 00:10:23.220
It wasn't anybody
in the scene.

00:10:23.220 --> 00:10:25.100
That's a helpful thing.

00:10:25.100 --> 00:10:30.720
Dialogue is the most readable
form of prose that there is.

00:10:30.720 --> 00:10:34.590
And you can go on and on in
dialogue, and in long

00:10:34.590 --> 00:10:35.550
sentences, anything.

00:10:35.550 --> 00:10:39.130
People will still find
it easy to read.

00:10:39.130 --> 00:10:42.490
Now, the movies can do both of
those things better than the

00:10:42.490 --> 00:10:44.790
written word.

00:10:44.790 --> 00:10:48.310
Scene-by-scene construction
and dialogue.

00:10:48.310 --> 00:10:53.860
But there are two things the
written word does better than

00:10:53.860 --> 00:10:57.660
anything that has yet
been invented.

00:10:57.660 --> 00:11:00.960
I signed all these releases
that said that you'd give

00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:05.510
whoever it is right for every
device they can think of, and

00:11:05.510 --> 00:11:09.640
it says "and anything invented
in the future." Well, suppose

00:11:09.640 --> 00:11:14.420
there's some sexual apparatus
you read by.

00:11:14.420 --> 00:11:15.740
I don't want be--

00:11:15.740 --> 00:11:18.010
I almost crossed that out.

00:11:18.010 --> 00:11:20.440
I don't want to be involved
in that kind of stuff.

00:11:20.440 --> 00:11:23.190
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:23.190 --> 00:11:27.310
TOM WOLFE: Anyway, notation
of status details.

00:11:27.310 --> 00:11:28.760
Movies cannot handle that.

00:11:28.760 --> 00:11:30.010
I'll give an example.

00:11:32.750 --> 00:11:34.410
I don't what the hot
loafers are today.

00:11:34.410 --> 00:11:35.610
But it was Gucci loafers.

00:11:35.610 --> 00:11:37.240
They were expensive.

00:11:37.240 --> 00:11:40.350
They were considered
high class.

00:11:40.350 --> 00:11:44.850
But you can show on the screen
a pair of Gucci loafers--

00:11:44.850 --> 00:11:45.400
RICK KLEFFEL: Nobody's
going to know what

00:11:45.400 --> 00:11:45.960
the hell they are.

00:11:45.960 --> 00:11:46.230
TOM WOLFE: Yeah.

00:11:46.230 --> 00:11:47.720
They want to know why that
camera's lingering on those

00:11:47.720 --> 00:11:48.970
dumb pair of shoes.

00:11:51.190 --> 00:11:56.450
They have a golden crossbar
that links in the middle.

00:11:59.010 --> 00:12:04.030
But in writing, it's nothing
to point these things out.

00:12:04.030 --> 00:12:10.060
And in the Godfather, when they
want to show that this

00:12:10.060 --> 00:12:13.350
one character-- he's not
a mafia character--

00:12:13.350 --> 00:12:15.910
one character is decadent.

00:12:15.910 --> 00:12:18.460
They have him living in a house
that would have made the

00:12:18.460 --> 00:12:19.470
Borgias shrink.

00:12:19.470 --> 00:12:22.320
Oh my god, look at
the size of that.

00:12:22.320 --> 00:12:29.550
And there's a famous scene,
where they cut off the head of

00:12:29.550 --> 00:12:31.510
one of his race horses.

00:12:31.510 --> 00:12:34.140
And they sneak into the room
while he's asleep, and they

00:12:34.140 --> 00:12:36.980
put it on the bed, so that he'll
wake up, and he'll see

00:12:36.980 --> 00:12:43.020
his great thoroughbred head
at the foot of the bed.

00:12:43.020 --> 00:12:48.280
But to let you know he's
decadent, they have to get him

00:12:48.280 --> 00:12:54.380
silk salmon-colored sheets,
a bed that you could play

00:12:54.380 --> 00:12:58.440
soccer, and with every
sort of trimming.

00:12:58.440 --> 00:13:01.620
In writing, you do not have
to go to all that trouble.

00:13:01.620 --> 00:13:08.380
As I say that 98% of life is
concerned, for everybody, with

00:13:08.380 --> 00:13:10.970
status, as I call it.

00:13:10.970 --> 00:13:11.460
RICK KLEFFEL: Class.

00:13:11.460 --> 00:13:12.700
And that's a big part
of this book.

00:13:12.700 --> 00:13:16.100
TOM WOLFE: Even people doing
things that are absolutely

00:13:16.100 --> 00:13:23.360
solitary, like going
to the bat-room.

00:13:23.360 --> 00:13:25.462
I used to call it
the bat-room.

00:13:25.462 --> 00:13:28.030
At home, with family, I just
say, I've got to go check on

00:13:28.030 --> 00:13:28.870
the Batmobile.

00:13:28.870 --> 00:13:29.570
What are you talking about?

00:13:29.570 --> 00:13:30.760
It's in the bat-room.

00:13:30.760 --> 00:13:33.430
Anyway, that's child talk.

00:13:33.430 --> 00:13:34.680
I'm sorry.

00:13:38.030 --> 00:13:41.070
Just think about it some time.

00:13:41.070 --> 00:13:46.500
The things that you do in total
privacy of any kind that

00:13:46.500 --> 00:13:50.610
you do because of your idea of
where this puts you in the

00:13:50.610 --> 00:13:51.570
social order.

00:13:51.570 --> 00:13:55.710
And it doesn't mean you want to
rise in the social order.

00:13:55.710 --> 00:13:57.590
I grew up in the South,
and I've known a

00:13:57.590 --> 00:13:58.710
lot of good old boys.

00:13:58.710 --> 00:14:00.030
I really have.

00:14:00.030 --> 00:14:03.570
And they don't realize how they
think they're dressing

00:14:03.570 --> 00:14:04.990
really casually.

