00:27:56.930 --> 00:27:59.170
Christmas tree farm.

00:27:59.170 --> 00:28:02.645
You just have to go through
all those prickly--

00:28:06.830 --> 00:28:08.710
well, they're like
thorns almost.

00:28:08.710 --> 00:28:12.670
RICK KLEFFEL: Well, you give us
a great vision of a Miami

00:28:12.670 --> 00:28:17.010
where most of the population
is not white,

00:28:17.010 --> 00:28:18.660
where it's run by Cubans.

00:28:18.660 --> 00:28:22.790
And you also have a lot
of fun with the media

00:28:22.790 --> 00:28:24.850
in this, and art.

00:28:24.850 --> 00:28:26.610
You do some fun things
with art.

00:28:26.610 --> 00:28:28.660
Is a really a no-hands
art movement?

00:28:28.660 --> 00:28:29.650
TOM WOLFE: Yes, there is.

00:28:29.650 --> 00:28:32.780
I'll tell you, it's
a very powerful

00:28:32.780 --> 00:28:34.340
movement in terms of--

00:28:34.340 --> 00:28:34.800
RICK KLEFFEL: Really?

00:28:34.800 --> 00:28:37.300
TOM WOLFE: --the art critics.

00:28:37.300 --> 00:28:38.010
Jeff Koons--

00:28:38.010 --> 00:28:40.630
you may know his work.

00:28:40.630 --> 00:28:42.170
He builds-- pff.

00:28:42.170 --> 00:28:48.500
"Builds." He has elves build
45-foot-high bunny rabbits,

00:28:48.500 --> 00:28:51.650
with various vegetation growing
on them to give them a

00:28:51.650 --> 00:28:53.802
kind of look like fur.

00:28:53.802 --> 00:28:55.820
He doesn't touch that,
of course.

00:28:55.820 --> 00:28:58.230
RICK KLEFFEL: It sounds
like a giant Chia Pet.

00:28:58.230 --> 00:28:59.870
TOM WOLFE: Yeah.

00:28:59.870 --> 00:29:02.680
He also had some photographs.

00:29:02.680 --> 00:29:04.140
I think he actually
married her.

00:29:04.140 --> 00:29:06.810
A very famous Italian prostitute
called "La

00:29:06.810 --> 00:29:08.300
Cicciolina".

00:29:08.300 --> 00:29:12.350
And she was famous because she
had messed up somebody's

00:29:12.350 --> 00:29:14.590
political career.

00:29:14.590 --> 00:29:15.800
And they were together.

00:29:15.800 --> 00:29:25.220
And he would have photographs
taken of himself and La

00:29:25.220 --> 00:29:31.420
Cicciolina exploring
about every orifice

00:29:31.420 --> 00:29:32.070
in the human body.

00:29:32.070 --> 00:29:34.680
I mean these were unbelievable
scenes.

00:29:34.680 --> 00:29:39.570
These were sent to elves in
Switzerland, who created them

00:29:39.570 --> 00:29:40.620
out of glass.

00:29:40.620 --> 00:29:43.900
They're kind of like Limoges.

00:29:43.900 --> 00:29:45.470
RICK KLEFFEL: So that's real?

00:29:45.470 --> 00:29:45.900
TOM WOLFE: That's real.

00:29:45.900 --> 00:29:46.400
Absolutely.

00:29:46.400 --> 00:29:47.770
RICK KLEFFEL: Oh my god.

00:29:47.770 --> 00:29:51.255
TOM WOLFE: And they fetch--

00:29:51.255 --> 00:29:52.385
A, he never touched
the camera.

00:29:52.385 --> 00:29:56.310
And I doubt if he even mails
them to the elves.

00:29:56.310 --> 00:29:58.190
He has people who
do that for him.

00:30:01.030 --> 00:30:05.340
These objects are
three-dimensional and glass.

00:30:05.340 --> 00:30:07.700
But so what that he didn't
touch, that he had nothing to

00:30:07.700 --> 00:30:09.110
do with it?

00:30:09.110 --> 00:30:13.300
They sell for fantastic
prices.

00:30:13.300 --> 00:30:18.860
1.7 million for him and La
Cicciolina in glass.

00:30:18.860 --> 00:30:21.200
It is not uncommon.

00:30:21.200 --> 00:30:21.990
RICK KLEFFEL: Did
you attend the

00:30:21.990 --> 00:30:25.360
Superbowl of art criticism?

00:30:25.360 --> 00:30:28.100
TOM WOLFE: Oh, I did.

00:30:28.100 --> 00:30:29.630
RICK KLEFFEL: Did you have
an AA to show you

00:30:29.630 --> 00:30:32.020
which ones were valuable?

00:30:32.020 --> 00:30:34.620
TOM WOLFE: Oh, actually,
I did.

00:30:34.620 --> 00:30:38.680
RICK KLEFFEL: So this is an
event where people go in.

00:30:38.680 --> 00:30:40.660
It's millionaires lining
up, as you

00:30:40.660 --> 00:30:42.240
describe it, like maggots.

00:30:42.240 --> 00:30:46.680
TOM WOLFE: Well, the most
noted ones were actually

00:30:46.680 --> 00:30:47.300
billionaires.

00:30:47.300 --> 00:30:50.380
There were 12 in line
when I went there.

00:30:50.380 --> 00:30:53.700
I had to wangle my way
to be in that line.

00:30:53.700 --> 00:30:58.710
It's the most privileged line at
the Miami Art Basel, which

00:30:58.710 --> 00:31:06.500
is an international art show
of supposedly serious art.

00:31:06.500 --> 00:31:08.320
And these--

00:31:08.320 --> 00:31:12.390
and I'm not kidding--
billionaires get in line.

00:31:12.390 --> 00:31:16.580
And these are people who are not
young, but they're wearing

00:31:16.580 --> 00:31:22.810
basketball shoes so that they
can get into the booth of the

00:31:22.810 --> 00:31:25.590
artist that they really
want first.

00:31:25.590 --> 00:31:28.750
And the fact that they're going
to rush in and pay $17

00:31:28.750 --> 00:31:31.770
million for something
is no problem.

00:31:31.770 --> 00:31:33.766
That is not a deterrent.

00:31:33.766 --> 00:31:35.540
RICK KLEFFEL: This is Black
Friday for millionaires.

00:31:35.540 --> 00:31:36.790
TOM WOLFE: Yeah.

00:31:40.940 --> 00:31:43.020
I couldn't believe it, so I
wrote it, to make sure I

00:31:43.020 --> 00:31:45.230
didn't forget it.

00:31:45.230 --> 00:31:46.960
It's an extraordinary thing.

00:31:46.960 --> 00:31:56.530
But all it they all have, as
you alluded, advisers they

00:31:56.530 --> 00:32:00.890
call AAs who tell them
what they like.

00:32:00.890 --> 00:32:03.410
You like that.

00:32:03.410 --> 00:32:08.470
And it's just no telling what
that may turn out to be.

00:32:08.470 --> 00:32:11.330
Oh, there's also tenure art.

00:32:11.330 --> 00:32:13.060
We mustn't forget tenure art.

00:32:13.060 --> 00:32:18.140
T-E-N-U-R-E. These are artists
who do conceptual pieces, such

00:32:18.140 --> 00:32:20.230
as one that I saw, and
actually rather

00:32:20.230 --> 00:32:21.830
enjoyed, in a way.

00:32:21.830 --> 00:32:23.150
The artist--

00:32:23.150 --> 00:32:24.360
"artist"--

00:32:24.360 --> 00:32:28.350
had a heavy chain, the length
was about this long.

00:32:28.350 --> 00:32:32.030
On either end, he had attached
big polyurethane bags filled

00:32:32.030 --> 00:32:34.250
with vegetables.

00:32:34.250 --> 00:32:38.070
And the first part of the piece
of art is you come out,

00:32:38.070 --> 00:32:42.060
and he lays the chain on
the top of a pond.

00:32:42.060 --> 00:32:45.090
Naturally, it sinks right
to the bottom.

00:32:45.090 --> 00:32:48.470
And then he invites you back in
about two months, and you

00:32:48.470 --> 00:32:49.990
go out to the pond.

00:32:49.990 --> 00:32:55.460
And now, the vegetables have
all rotted, filling the

00:32:55.460 --> 00:32:57.790
polyurethane bags with gas.

00:32:57.790 --> 00:33:00.930
And now the chain is floating
on the surface.

00:33:00.930 --> 00:33:04.010
And I will admit, it's pretty
wonderful to, if you saw it

00:33:04.010 --> 00:33:06.170
sink the first time.

00:33:06.170 --> 00:33:10.720
But now this, obviously, cannot
be sold to anybody.

00:33:10.720 --> 00:33:15.320
Another piece I saw an action
was a pig roast.

00:33:15.320 --> 00:33:17.220
And the Caja China-- that's
a Cuban grill.

00:33:19.880 --> 00:33:23.600
And the whole piece of the
artwork was seeing them

00:33:23.600 --> 00:33:27.030
prepare the pig, and seeing
the pig roasting.

00:33:27.030 --> 00:33:29.640
and we're talking about
an 8-hour show now.

00:33:29.640 --> 00:33:34.670
And then afterwards, everyone
who's there eats the pig.

00:33:34.670 --> 00:33:37.180
That's another piece
of tenure art.

00:33:37.180 --> 00:33:39.910
The idea is, if you do enough
of these things that attract

00:33:39.910 --> 00:33:43.640
attention, and maybe get you
into some of the magazines,

00:33:43.640 --> 00:33:49.510
you have a pretty good shot at
joining the fine arts faculty

00:33:49.510 --> 00:33:51.975
of a good university.

00:33:51.975 --> 00:33:56.140
And if you can hang in there for
six years-- that's all it

00:33:56.140 --> 00:33:58.010
takes now--

00:33:58.010 --> 00:33:58.980
that's tenure.

00:33:58.980 --> 00:34:00.580
You have tenure.

00:34:00.580 --> 00:34:07.455
And when you retire, you have
a pretty level pension.

00:34:10.159 --> 00:34:14.699
Depending on your needs
and wants and desires,

00:34:14.699 --> 00:34:16.510
your life is set.

00:34:16.510 --> 00:34:18.750
RICK KLEFFEL: I don't need
much more and two bags of

00:34:18.750 --> 00:34:20.790
vegetables and a chain link.

00:34:20.790 --> 00:34:21.500
TOM WOLFE: It's been done.

00:34:21.500 --> 00:34:22.920
It's been done.

00:34:22.920 --> 00:34:26.949
The important thing is
it hasn't been done.

00:34:26.949 --> 00:34:28.510
Well, I've given up.

00:34:28.510 --> 00:34:31.170
I found this all great,
because for a

00:34:31.170 --> 00:34:32.370
writer, it's all gold.

00:34:32.370 --> 00:34:33.489
It's absolutely gold.

00:34:33.489 --> 00:34:36.690
One of the main terms at Yale
today in the fine arts

00:34:36.690 --> 00:34:39.780
department is de-skilled art.

00:34:39.780 --> 00:34:41.540
The idea is that all
of this drawing--

00:34:41.540 --> 00:34:43.960
[AUDIO CUTS OUT]

00:34:43.960 --> 00:34:46.499
TOM WOLFE: --three dimensional
effects, it's very--

00:34:46.499 --> 00:34:49.610
[AUDIO CUTS OUT]

00:34:49.610 --> 00:34:51.810
TOM WOLFE: --the reader, that
person who's done in an

00:34:51.810 --> 00:34:55.250
outline, that person
doesn't exist.

00:34:55.250 --> 00:34:57.590
And the three dimension.

00:34:57.590 --> 00:34:58.820
Come on, touch the damn thing.

00:34:58.820 --> 00:35:01.750
It's just absolutely flat.

00:35:01.750 --> 00:35:03.760
That's deception.

00:35:03.760 --> 00:35:07.690
So what you have to do is have
honest art, which is

00:35:07.690 --> 00:35:08.880
de-skilled.

00:35:08.880 --> 00:35:10.825
You've just got to take
the skill out of it.

00:35:14.700 --> 00:35:16.330
This I really shouldn't
say, but I think

00:35:16.330 --> 00:35:19.750
that describes Picasso.

00:35:19.750 --> 00:35:22.220
RICK KLEFFEL: Well, he shows
up in your book, too.

00:35:22.220 --> 00:35:24.620
TOM WOLFE: He does pop in.

00:35:24.620 --> 00:35:26.880
I have said this before, so
I shouldn't repeat it.

00:35:26.880 --> 00:35:29.200
But if I couldn't--

00:35:29.200 --> 00:35:30.110
I'm talking about me.

00:35:30.110 --> 00:35:31.980
I'm not talking about
some journal--

00:35:31.980 --> 00:35:32.760
RICK KLEFFEL: Don't worry.

00:35:32.760 --> 00:35:35.500
YouTube's going to repeat
it for you.

00:35:35.500 --> 00:35:40.470
TOM WOLFE: If I could not draw
better than Picasso, what I

00:35:40.470 --> 00:35:46.160
would do is create a movement
called cubism.

00:35:46.160 --> 00:35:50.290
And so that they don't think I'm
trying to draw a skilled

00:35:50.290 --> 00:35:55.555
face, I put both eyes on one
side of the head, and then the

00:35:55.555 --> 00:35:59.180
nose goes out somewhere
that noses never go.

00:35:59.180 --> 00:36:05.780
See, the problem with Picasso
was he left art school because

00:36:05.780 --> 00:36:07.560
at 15, he felt there
was nothing more

00:36:07.560 --> 00:36:09.530
they could teach him.

00:36:09.530 --> 00:36:12.380
Unfortunately, it was that next
some semester they began

00:36:12.380 --> 00:36:17.375
to teach anatomy and the third
dimension, perspective.

00:36:20.030 --> 00:36:23.660
So he had to do the
best he can.

00:36:23.660 --> 00:36:25.040
Look at early.

00:36:25.040 --> 00:36:29.190
He had more or less realistic in
the so-called Blue Period.

00:36:29.190 --> 00:36:32.010
Take a look at the fingers.

00:36:32.010 --> 00:36:34.970
They look like a clump of a
asparagus bought at the

00:36:34.970 --> 00:36:36.250
grocery store.

00:36:36.250 --> 00:36:38.190
They're all the same length.

00:36:38.190 --> 00:36:41.300
If he can, he hides them.

00:36:41.300 --> 00:36:44.210
Matisse also could
not do hands.

00:36:44.210 --> 00:36:48.830
And sometime, if you're just
rummaging through a book of

00:36:48.830 --> 00:36:51.500
art, and you come to Matisse,
just look at all the hands

00:36:51.500 --> 00:36:53.040
that are stuck behind
the back.

00:36:55.972 --> 00:36:58.780
I just think it's wonderful.

00:36:58.780 --> 00:37:01.720
People think I knock art.

00:37:01.720 --> 00:37:02.140
I don't.

00:37:02.140 --> 00:37:05.060
I never make a single
aesthetic judgment.

00:37:05.060 --> 00:37:08.106
I just tell how it happened.

00:37:08.106 --> 00:37:08.775
I swear.

00:37:08.775 --> 00:37:10.800
RICK KLEFFEL: Here, let me
help you with this guy.

00:37:10.800 --> 00:37:14.700
Now in this book,
we have a great

00:37:14.700 --> 00:37:16.820
look at American culture.

00:37:16.820 --> 00:37:23.470
And one of the things you give
us are how any single act that

00:37:23.470 --> 00:37:27.340
any of us does can be turned
into a dozen different acts

00:37:27.340 --> 00:37:30.790
depending on who's telling the
story, and how it's been told.

00:37:30.790 --> 00:37:33.680
At the center of this book is
Nestor Camacho, who does

00:37:33.680 --> 00:37:36.920
something that seems, at the
moment, quite valiant and

00:37:36.920 --> 00:37:37.620
incredible.

00:37:37.620 --> 00:37:42.700
But in the aftermath, it just
gets spun 10 different ways by

00:37:42.700 --> 00:37:44.420
10 different news
organizations.

00:37:44.420 --> 00:37:48.860
Talk about putting us in those
news perspectives.

00:37:48.860 --> 00:37:52.740
Did you intern yourself, so
to speak, with the Cuban

00:37:52.740 --> 00:37:55.710
newspaper, and the American
newspaper, and the bloggers,

00:37:55.710 --> 00:37:57.935
and all the other people that
you talk about in the book?

00:37:57.935 --> 00:38:00.900
TOM WOLFE: Fortunately, I
spent 10 years on the--

00:38:00.900 --> 00:38:02.070
I guess it was fortunate--

00:38:02.070 --> 00:38:04.085
10 years on newspapers.

00:38:04.085 --> 00:38:07.930
I felt I kind of knew the
drill from the newspaper

00:38:07.930 --> 00:38:09.280
perspective.

00:38:09.280 --> 00:38:13.830
In this particular case that
Rick's referring to, my

00:38:13.830 --> 00:38:16.450
central character's name
is Nestor Camacho.

00:38:16.450 --> 00:38:21.100
Nobody ever understands Cuban
first names, males

00:38:21.100 --> 00:38:22.190
particularly.

00:38:22.190 --> 00:38:26.480
Nestor was a great hero the
Trojan wars, but it drives him

00:38:26.480 --> 00:38:31.830
crazy, everybody, in Americano,
calls him

00:38:31.830 --> 00:38:36.960
"Nest-er." It ends in E-R.

00:38:36.960 --> 00:38:38.700
And I'll point out,
it's very unusual.

00:38:38.700 --> 00:38:41.240
He's on the Miami
Marine Patrol.

00:38:41.240 --> 00:38:44.880
Beyond the patrol is a step
up from walking a beat or

00:38:44.880 --> 00:38:47.740
something, or driving a beat.

00:38:47.740 --> 00:38:50.710
And he is in the probation
period.

00:38:50.710 --> 00:38:55.060
So on this safe boat,
they're called--

00:38:55.060 --> 00:38:57.550
wackiest looking boat you've
ever seen, but they go 45

00:38:57.550 --> 00:38:58.990
miles an hour on the water.

00:38:58.990 --> 00:39:02.750
They're for saving
people and boats.

00:39:02.750 --> 00:39:07.770
So he's on with two Anglos.

00:39:07.770 --> 00:39:09.680
I have to say, the Cubans
would never use

00:39:09.680 --> 00:39:10.600
the word like gringo.

00:39:10.600 --> 00:39:13.670
They will say Americano if
they're speaking among

00:39:13.670 --> 00:39:14.350
themselves.

00:39:14.350 --> 00:39:18.240
In general, it's Anglos
and Latinos.

00:39:18.240 --> 00:39:20.340
At the beginning of Florida--

00:39:20.340 --> 00:39:22.550
Southern Florida's the only
place on the face of the earth

00:39:22.550 --> 00:39:24.830
where anybody was ever
called a Latina, a

00:39:24.830 --> 00:39:27.300
Latino, or an Anglo.

00:39:27.300 --> 00:39:30.950
And an Anglo is of
European origin.

00:39:30.950 --> 00:39:34.460
But if he's not completely
white, he's not an Anglo.

00:39:34.460 --> 00:39:38.010
It all has to do with
skin color.

00:39:38.010 --> 00:39:42.430
Anyway, there are these two
Anglos, or Americanos, who

00:39:42.430 --> 00:39:44.030
outrank him on the boat.

00:39:44.030 --> 00:39:50.290
He is the third man, the young
man, he's on probation.

00:39:50.290 --> 00:39:57.000
And they're having a
conversation, and he says

00:39:57.000 --> 00:39:59.250
something that sounds
to the two

00:39:59.250 --> 00:40:01.150
Americanos as rather uppity.

00:40:01.150 --> 00:40:03.940
I'm thinking of the Sergeant,
or the man in chief.

00:40:03.940 --> 00:40:09.500
And Nestor's on probation,
and he goes, oh my god.

00:40:09.500 --> 00:40:14.470
This is bad, if I get washed
out of probation.

00:40:14.470 --> 00:40:18.830
So they are called to a
situation in which there's a

00:40:18.830 --> 00:40:21.520
Cuban refugee atop
a schooner mast.

00:40:21.520 --> 00:40:25.310
So he's up about 75, 80 feet.

00:40:25.310 --> 00:40:30.090
The boat is stopped right
near a causeway.

00:40:30.090 --> 00:40:34.230
Miami has lots of causeways
go across Biscayne Bay.

00:40:34.230 --> 00:40:37.290
And they've stopped, because
they're not sure that the mass

00:40:37.290 --> 00:40:41.470
will clear the bridge.

00:40:41.470 --> 00:40:43.480
And so they're trying to
figure out what to do.

00:40:43.480 --> 00:40:48.290
And this Cuban refugee, who
has obviously paid about

00:40:48.290 --> 00:40:52.210
$5,000, is brought
in by a cigarette

00:40:52.210 --> 00:40:53.280
boat, they're called.

00:40:53.280 --> 00:40:56.850
Those are the really fast,
small, good-looking boats.

00:40:56.850 --> 00:40:58.140
70 miles an hour.

00:40:58.140 --> 00:40:59.640
RICK KLEFFEL: Did
you ride on one?

00:40:59.640 --> 00:41:01.520
TOM WOLFE: I would have gladly
done it, but I didn't ride on

00:41:01.520 --> 00:41:02.400
one of those.

00:41:02.400 --> 00:41:04.980
I did ride on the marine
patrol boat.

00:41:04.980 --> 00:41:05.330
RICK KLEFFEL: Oh, really?

00:41:05.330 --> 00:41:05.630
TOM WOLFE: Yeah.

00:41:05.630 --> 00:41:07.370
Oh, yeah.

00:41:07.370 --> 00:41:09.230
I'd never heard of it myself.

00:41:09.230 --> 00:41:10.540
RICK KLEFFEL: Sounds like fun.

00:41:10.540 --> 00:41:12.850
TOM WOLFE: It was.

00:41:12.850 --> 00:41:15.760
That thing is really
hell on wheels.

00:41:15.760 --> 00:41:16.660
But it's the safe boat.

00:41:16.660 --> 00:41:17.960
It wasn't going to turn over.

00:41:17.960 --> 00:41:26.360
So they get there, and it turns
out that if a Cuban

00:41:26.360 --> 00:41:30.850
touches American soil, or
anything edifice that's

00:41:30.850 --> 00:41:36.660
jutting out from it, like a
jetty or a bridge, he cannot

00:41:36.660 --> 00:41:40.000
be sent back to Cuba.

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:42.020
If he's done something bad,
he can be prosecuted.

00:41:42.020 --> 00:41:43.940
But he cannot be sent back.

00:41:43.940 --> 00:41:48.550
But if you don't do that, you're
called a wetfoot, and

00:41:48.550 --> 00:41:50.730
you're sent back.

00:41:50.730 --> 00:41:54.870
Now, this fellow he apparently
wasn't--

00:41:54.870 --> 00:41:58.410
well, he was a little bit
deranged or confused.

00:41:58.410 --> 00:42:01.530
And he sees this ladder that
goes up, and he figures it

00:42:01.530 --> 00:42:03.860
goes up to a dock.

00:42:03.860 --> 00:42:07.230
In fact, it goes onto the
deck of a schooner.

00:42:07.230 --> 00:42:11.180
If you're on a schooner,
you're still a wetfoot.

00:42:11.180 --> 00:42:16.280
Even if the schooner is owned
by the governor of Florida,

00:42:16.280 --> 00:42:17.810
you're in bad luck.

00:42:17.810 --> 00:42:23.600
So this Camacho speaks
Spanish.

00:42:23.600 --> 00:42:26.180
Like a lot of second generation
Cubans, he speaks

00:42:26.180 --> 00:42:28.890
12-year-old Spanish.

00:42:28.890 --> 00:42:33.530
When they get a little older,
they'd rather see American

00:42:33.530 --> 00:42:37.760
television, learn
American ways.

00:42:37.760 --> 00:42:39.830
Their parents may be
kind of stuck--

00:42:39.830 --> 00:42:40.240
RICK KLEFFEL: Sure.

00:42:40.240 --> 00:42:42.520
It's easier to be immersed.

00:42:42.520 --> 00:42:48.110
And then the immigrant has
climbed up the mast, trying to

00:42:48.110 --> 00:42:51.090
maybe jump onto that causeway.

00:42:51.090 --> 00:42:51.440
TOM WOLFE: Yeah.

00:42:51.440 --> 00:42:54.750
And he was a little frightened
by the reaction of the owners

00:42:54.750 --> 00:42:55.355
of the ship.

00:42:55.355 --> 00:42:58.220
So he goes up on this mast.

00:42:58.220 --> 00:43:00.700
He's 75 feet up in the air.

00:43:00.700 --> 00:43:05.320
And so the two Anglos, or two
American crewman who outrank

00:43:05.320 --> 00:43:08.770
him said, you speak Spanish.

00:43:08.770 --> 00:43:14.020
Go on up there and tell
him to come down.

00:43:14.020 --> 00:43:16.700
He's tying up traffic
on the causeway.

00:43:16.700 --> 00:43:20.920
It's just a block of traffic.

00:43:20.920 --> 00:43:25.740
Because he's threatened with
being washed out of probation,

00:43:25.740 --> 00:43:29.560
he doesn't dare tell them that
he cannot speak anything above

00:43:29.560 --> 00:43:32.660
12-year-old Spanish.

00:43:32.660 --> 00:43:37.040
So he's very powerfully built.

00:43:37.040 --> 00:43:39.880
Incidentally, I don't know if
anybody here, any male who

00:43:39.880 --> 00:43:42.920
really wants to be powerfully
built, but you cannot top rope

00:43:42.920 --> 00:43:44.300
climbing without using
your legs.

00:43:44.300 --> 00:43:46.140
RICK KLEFFEL: That's a big
theme of this book.

00:43:46.140 --> 00:43:47.900
Get out there and rope
climb, guys.

00:43:47.900 --> 00:43:49.500
TOM WOLFE: To climb ropes,
you can't use your legs.

00:43:49.500 --> 00:43:50.990
Can't use your legs.

00:43:50.990 --> 00:43:54.040
Anyway, he does this, because
the quickest way to go up,

00:43:54.040 --> 00:43:57.600
it's much quicker to go up
without using your legs, if

00:43:57.600 --> 00:44:01.370
you have the strength, than
to stop or use them.

00:44:01.370 --> 00:44:04.140
So he climbs all the way
up, and he gets within

00:44:04.140 --> 00:44:05.950
10 feet of the guy.

00:44:05.950 --> 00:44:12.160
And he realizes if you
are fleeing from a

00:44:12.160 --> 00:44:14.000
credible threat in Cuba--

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:17.770
that's the word, a
credible threat--

00:44:17.770 --> 00:44:21.330
they're not going
to arrest you.

00:44:21.330 --> 00:44:25.420
Miami police never arrest
an illegal immigrants.

00:44:25.420 --> 00:44:27.580
They leave that up to the
federal government.

00:44:27.580 --> 00:44:29.455
They have enough people to make
enemies with as it is.

00:44:32.240 --> 00:44:36.860
So he's practically up to the
guy, and he doesn't know the

00:44:36.860 --> 00:44:38.300
word for threat.

00:44:38.300 --> 00:44:40.440
And this may seem strange,
because it's the same word as

00:44:40.440 --> 00:44:41.060
in English.

00:44:41.060 --> 00:44:45.290
He also does not know the word
"credible," or credible.

00:44:45.290 --> 00:44:48.880
Because it's just not a word
a 12-year-old uses.

00:44:48.880 --> 00:44:50.580
RICK KLEFFEL: Sure.

00:44:50.580 --> 00:44:54.300
TOM WOLFE: He's actually
26 in this scene.

00:44:54.300 --> 00:44:56.890
So he gets up there, and
he doesn't know what

00:44:56.890 --> 00:44:58.550
to say to the guy.

00:44:58.550 --> 00:45:01.870
So he starts flashing
the peace sign.

00:45:01.870 --> 00:45:05.440
And that only frightens--

00:45:05.440 --> 00:45:06.430
they could be devil's horns.

00:45:06.430 --> 00:45:08.810
Who knows what he's flashing
at the guy.

00:45:08.810 --> 00:45:12.830
So he doesn't respond-- in fact,
he tries to get up out

00:45:12.830 --> 00:45:16.050
of this little bosun chair that
he's nestled in at the

00:45:16.050 --> 00:45:17.820
top of the mast.

00:45:17.820 --> 00:45:22.060
And he gets up, and he starts
trying to get away by going

00:45:22.060 --> 00:45:25.975
down the jib.

00:45:25.975 --> 00:45:28.435
RICK KLEFFEL: The triangulation,
right?

00:45:28.435 --> 00:45:28.830
To the bow.

00:45:28.830 --> 00:45:30.660
TOM WOLFE: That cable that
goes to the bow.

00:45:30.660 --> 00:45:37.290
And he's not strong enough,
this fellow from Cuba.

00:45:37.290 --> 00:45:43.320
And so Nestor, my friend, climbs
down, hand-over-hand

00:45:43.320 --> 00:45:47.140
down, and then wraps his legs
around the this guy.

00:45:47.140 --> 00:45:50.670
He's not very big, maybe
120, 130 pounds.

00:45:50.670 --> 00:45:56.750
And carries him down, all the
way down the jib line, which

00:45:56.750 --> 00:45:58.080
leads you, actually,
into the water.

00:45:58.080 --> 00:45:59.840
Because it juts out
over the prow.

00:45:59.840 --> 00:46:01.000
And they fall into the water.

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:03.040
The guy fights him.

00:46:03.040 --> 00:46:03.690
He's fighting him.

00:46:03.690 --> 00:46:06.050
He think he's going to take him
and turn him in and send

00:46:06.050 --> 00:46:07.300
him back to Cuba.

00:46:09.600 --> 00:46:14.720
And at first, his police
brethren say, my god--

00:46:14.720 --> 00:46:17.570
Police don't use the
word "bravery." Jet

00:46:17.570 --> 00:46:18.820
pilots don't either.

00:46:21.150 --> 00:46:24.320
They'll say, that was an
unacceptable level of risk in

00:46:24.320 --> 00:46:24.880
that operation.

00:46:24.880 --> 00:46:26.220
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:26.220 --> 00:46:28.180
TOM WOLFE: That's about
as close as they get.

00:46:28.180 --> 00:46:31.540
But anyway, they were all proud
of him, the police--

00:46:31.540 --> 00:46:35.360
who are mostly Cuban.

00:46:35.360 --> 00:46:35.590
so.

00:46:35.590 --> 00:46:39.260
He's really happy, and
then he goes home.

00:46:39.260 --> 00:46:40.620
It's now after midnight.

00:46:40.620 --> 00:46:43.690
It was the four to
midnight shift.

00:46:43.690 --> 00:46:48.300
And he expects to get all
this adulation at home.

00:46:48.300 --> 00:46:51.430
And instead, he walks in,
here's his father.

00:46:51.430 --> 00:46:53.540
His arms crossed like this.

00:46:53.540 --> 00:46:54.770
RICK KLEFFEL: "Aye, Carmillo."

00:46:54.770 --> 00:46:58.500
TOM WOLFE: Aye, Carmillo
Camacho.

00:46:58.500 --> 00:46:59.750
That's the last name.

00:47:02.360 --> 00:47:10.070
I and your woman who became your
mother spent 12 days at

00:47:10.070 --> 00:47:14.020
sea on a homemade dinghy.

00:47:14.020 --> 00:47:17.000
We had to make it an apartment
because the block wardens

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:21.130
would have detected it if we
had tried to do it outside.

00:47:21.130 --> 00:47:22.870
We almost died 100 times.

00:47:22.870 --> 00:47:25.680
We finally made it, thank
god, to Key West.

00:47:25.680 --> 00:47:28.140
We came aland, and we all live--
and your grandparents,

00:47:28.140 --> 00:47:30.650
too, who were living
in that house.

00:47:30.650 --> 00:47:32.750
And happy to do this.

00:47:32.750 --> 00:47:34.990
You've drag our name
through the mud.

00:47:34.990 --> 00:47:35.850
Poor guy.

00:47:35.850 --> 00:47:38.590
"They ordered me!" Ah, yes,
they ordered people in

00:47:38.590 --> 00:47:39.840
Germany, too.

00:47:41.900 --> 00:47:42.990
He couldn't get away
with that, they

00:47:42.990 --> 00:47:44.620
ordered me to do it.

00:47:44.620 --> 00:47:47.890
And then everybody turns
against him.

00:47:47.890 --> 00:47:49.680
RICK KLEFFEL: This is a
book that is really

00:47:49.680 --> 00:47:51.180
involved with guilt.

00:47:51.180 --> 00:47:52.850
There's a lot of guilt
in this book.

00:47:52.850 --> 00:47:54.570
You really have a lot
of fun with guilt.

00:47:54.570 --> 00:47:57.490
You know, I've just got to say
that you had a lot of fun in

00:47:57.490 --> 00:47:58.930
this book, didn't you?

00:47:58.930 --> 00:48:00.550
Writing this book, putting
this together.

00:48:00.550 --> 00:48:03.110
You must have spent
a lot of time.

00:48:03.110 --> 00:48:04.900
It sounds like this
is a book that you

00:48:04.900 --> 00:48:06.160
had a good time writing.

00:48:06.160 --> 00:48:06.700
TOM WOLFE: Oh, no.

00:48:06.700 --> 00:48:08.500
I've never had a good time
writing anything.

00:48:08.500 --> 00:48:11.320
I think it's the hardest
work in the world.

00:48:11.320 --> 00:48:14.870
The only thing that gets you
through is that, maybe

00:48:14.870 --> 00:48:16.860
somebody will applaud
when it's over.

00:48:16.860 --> 00:48:18.610
RICK KLEFFEL: Well, now, these
people are going to applaud.

00:48:18.610 --> 00:48:19.370
But I think some of them--

00:48:19.370 --> 00:48:21.330
TOM WOLFE: No, you don't
have to applaud.

00:48:21.330 --> 00:48:22.300
You haven't read the book.

00:48:22.300 --> 00:48:23.590
RICK KLEFFEL: Some of them might
have some questions.

00:48:23.590 --> 00:48:24.570
Does anybody out there have any

00:48:24.570 --> 00:48:28.040
questions for Mr. Tom Wolfe?

00:48:28.040 --> 00:48:29.520
AUDIENCE: Thank you
for coming.

00:48:29.520 --> 00:48:30.610
Aspiring novelist.

00:48:30.610 --> 00:48:32.680
Written one really bad book.

00:48:32.680 --> 00:48:36.180
I'm hoping that the next
one isn't as bad.

00:48:36.180 --> 00:48:42.700
Any advice for going from short
stories up to something

00:48:42.700 --> 00:48:47.160
all encompassing and substantial
as this?

00:48:47.160 --> 00:48:48.685
TOM WOLFE: Well, first of all,
you can't make a living on

00:48:48.685 --> 00:48:50.940
short stories.

00:48:50.940 --> 00:48:52.060
It's very hard.

00:48:52.060 --> 00:48:53.360
AUDIENCE: That's why I'm
a software engineer.

00:48:53.360 --> 00:48:55.580
[LAUGHTER]

00:48:55.580 --> 00:48:57.240
TOM WOLFE: It's very hard.

00:48:57.240 --> 00:49:01.790
But in my case, what gets me the
point of writing something

00:49:01.790 --> 00:49:07.400
that long is I will hear
of a certainly milieu.

00:49:07.400 --> 00:49:09.970
And except for my book on the
astronauts, is always been

00:49:09.970 --> 00:49:13.890
things I heard through
conversation.

00:49:13.890 --> 00:49:16.460
That way, I figure
it'll be new.

00:49:16.460 --> 00:49:20.080
If it's new for me, it's
probably new for most people.

00:49:20.080 --> 00:49:23.130
And wherever that's happening,
I will go.

00:49:23.130 --> 00:49:27.450
My motto is "leave the
building." I'll go there and

00:49:27.450 --> 00:49:32.600
try to just learn as
much as I can.

00:49:32.600 --> 00:49:34.220
Like the man from Mars.

00:49:34.220 --> 00:49:35.200
I don't know what
you're doing.

00:49:35.200 --> 00:49:36.020
I'm really interested.

00:49:36.020 --> 00:49:38.222
And it's true.

00:49:38.222 --> 00:49:41.780
That's what I'm like
when I'm there.

00:49:41.780 --> 00:49:44.760
And I think it's important--

00:49:44.760 --> 00:49:47.950
and this may sound like--

00:49:47.950 --> 00:49:50.690
but it's not hot air.

00:49:50.690 --> 00:49:53.030
It's important to have
a concept of life.

00:49:53.030 --> 00:49:55.770
I really believe that.

00:49:55.770 --> 00:50:02.140
In my case, it's the theory of
status as was developed by Max

00:50:02.140 --> 00:50:04.890
Weber, German sociologist.

00:50:04.890 --> 00:50:08.610
But there are people who have
done great things with, let's

00:50:08.610 --> 00:50:09.860
say, Christianity.

00:50:11.750 --> 00:50:16.320
There's so many pieces to great
literature that come out

00:50:16.320 --> 00:50:16.920
of a belief.

00:50:16.920 --> 00:50:21.780
Marxism has not done badly, that
many of the good writers

00:50:21.780 --> 00:50:27.630
in America in the 1930s and
the '40s were Marxists.

00:50:27.630 --> 00:50:29.830
The thing about Marxism
that's good--

00:50:29.830 --> 00:50:31.270
not much else is--

00:50:31.270 --> 00:50:38.930
is that it forces you to
recognize class distinctions.

00:50:38.930 --> 00:50:41.910
And class is not a very
accurate word

00:50:41.910 --> 00:50:43.160
in the United States.

00:50:45.270 --> 00:50:48.380
But still, it forces
you do it.

00:50:48.380 --> 00:50:52.360
And you suddenly become
conscious of a working class.

00:50:52.360 --> 00:50:56.280
You become conscious
of a bourgeoisie.

00:50:56.280 --> 00:51:02.710
And oddly, they never
get after the

00:51:02.710 --> 00:51:04.555
plutocrats very much.

00:51:04.555 --> 00:51:06.330
I don't know why.

00:51:06.330 --> 00:51:07.980
Sometime, look at some
Marxist literature.

00:51:07.980 --> 00:51:09.590
They kind of leave them alone.

00:51:09.590 --> 00:51:12.430
But the bourgeoisie--

00:51:12.430 --> 00:51:18.070
But it is a way of noticing how
society is put together.

00:51:18.070 --> 00:51:23.820
Max Weber, I think, made
the Marxist breakdown--

00:51:23.820 --> 00:51:27.970
he wasn't a Marxist, but
much more subtle.

00:51:27.970 --> 00:51:36.490
Because I think most of us feel
that we are in a certain

00:51:36.490 --> 00:51:49.480
status group, and that we live
by a set of values that are

00:51:49.480 --> 00:51:55.850
natural to this group, which,
if chiseled in stone by God,

00:51:55.850 --> 00:51:58.400
would make you supreme.

00:51:58.400 --> 00:52:02.590
Not you, your group.

00:52:02.590 --> 00:52:06.000
The essential thing
is the group.

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:10.270
And in a case like mine,
I'm in a group

00:52:10.270 --> 00:52:13.340
of people who write.

00:52:13.340 --> 00:52:15.400
I include even journalists
in the

00:52:15.400 --> 00:52:23.980
group, and serious writers.

00:52:23.980 --> 00:52:27.690
But then, I also grew up
in Richmond, Virginia.

00:52:27.690 --> 00:52:30.040
And every now and then, without
my knowing it--

00:52:30.040 --> 00:52:31.290
I'll give a good example.

00:52:36.770 --> 00:52:41.370
When these two Virginians--

00:52:41.370 --> 00:52:48.330
Pat Robinson the evangelist,
and the evangelist from

00:52:48.330 --> 00:52:51.720
Lynchburg, Virginia,
Jerry Falwell--

00:52:51.720 --> 00:52:58.190
When they came out protesting,
at a really key point early in

00:52:58.190 --> 00:53:05.040
the game, same-sex marriage
as an absolute violation.

00:53:05.040 --> 00:53:07.150
Oh, it was worse than that.

00:53:07.150 --> 00:53:08.870
It was different from that.

00:53:08.870 --> 00:53:19.670
They blamed September 11,
2001 on homosexuality.

00:53:19.670 --> 00:53:22.850
And my god, they were torn
to bits by [INAUDIBLE].

00:53:22.850 --> 00:53:23.910
And I said, wait a minute!

00:53:23.910 --> 00:53:25.570
These two guys are not bad.

00:53:25.570 --> 00:53:29.710
Pat Robinson went to the
college I went to.

00:53:29.710 --> 00:53:30.650
Maybe they're wrong.

00:53:30.650 --> 00:53:32.315
But they're not evil.

00:53:35.050 --> 00:53:37.340
Many of us have a duel.

00:53:37.340 --> 00:53:40.170
We'll find ourselves being loyal
to our backgrounds, when

00:53:40.170 --> 00:53:42.630
we'd never even thought
about it.

00:53:42.630 --> 00:53:45.870
But there tend to
be these groups.

00:53:45.870 --> 00:53:50.820
People who are in the arts,
believe me, they have a real

00:53:50.820 --> 00:53:52.440
different set of values.

00:53:52.440 --> 00:53:55.110
RICK KLEFFEL: We have another
question over there.

00:53:55.110 --> 00:53:56.620
LOGAN: Hi, my name is Logan.

00:53:56.620 --> 00:53:57.930
Thank you so much for coming.

00:53:57.930 --> 00:53:59.170
It's an honor to
have you here.

00:53:59.170 --> 00:53:59.840
TOM WOLFE: Well,
you're welcome.

00:53:59.840 --> 00:54:01.930
LOGAN: As someone who's spent
his career interested in

00:54:01.930 --> 00:54:04.740
class, and observing class in
America, I was wondering if

00:54:04.740 --> 00:54:07.180
you could speak a little bit
about this election cycle.

00:54:07.180 --> 00:54:09.900
I feel like that's something
that's really come up a lot.

00:54:09.900 --> 00:54:12.670
And even in the last six months,
and before that with

00:54:12.670 --> 00:54:14.240
Occupy Wall Street, it's
very relevant.

00:54:14.240 --> 00:54:16.230
So I'd love to hear your
opinion about that.

00:54:18.920 --> 00:54:21.140
TOM WOLFE: They've tried, and
the press has tried to help,

00:54:21.140 --> 00:54:27.340
too, to turn this into
a class election.

00:54:27.340 --> 00:54:30.710
The 1% against the 99%.

00:54:30.710 --> 00:54:34.990
Somewhere, the lower
class disappeared.

00:54:34.990 --> 00:54:38.270
Everyone talks about
the middle class.

00:54:38.270 --> 00:54:40.350
What's this middle class?

00:54:40.350 --> 00:54:41.520
I don't get it.

00:54:41.520 --> 00:54:42.710
Whatever you want it to be.

00:54:42.710 --> 00:54:43.860
It includes,

00:54:43.860 --> 00:54:46.280
RICK KLEFFEL: Tyrannosaurus
rex, brontosaurus--

00:54:46.280 --> 00:54:51.000
TOM WOLFE: Anybody who is
employed even as an intern is

00:54:51.000 --> 00:54:54.145
part of the middle class now.

00:54:54.145 --> 00:54:58.160
And on both sides, we hear--

00:54:58.160 --> 00:55:02.980
Mitt Romney and his
first rally I saw.

00:55:02.980 --> 00:55:06.640
I mean, my god, are his
beginnings humble.

00:55:06.640 --> 00:55:07.630
Obama, the same way.

00:55:07.630 --> 00:55:10.280
Oh my god, are his beginnings
humble.

00:55:10.280 --> 00:55:11.780
And he's come up from nowhere.

00:55:11.780 --> 00:55:14.290
So has Mitt Romney.

00:55:14.290 --> 00:55:20.560
This is not a sign of a
class-ridden society.

00:55:20.560 --> 00:55:26.940
If your credentials have to
include failure, obscurity,

00:55:26.940 --> 00:55:30.170
that's not a class-ridden
society.

00:55:30.170 --> 00:55:31.870
In England--

00:55:31.870 --> 00:55:34.370
probably the same thing's
true now--

00:55:34.370 --> 00:55:39.180
when people go to visit the
poor, they dress up.

00:55:39.180 --> 00:55:40.550
In a way, I suppose, to
show them what they

00:55:40.550 --> 00:55:42.220
could become someday.

00:55:42.220 --> 00:55:45.770
In this country, if we have a
contractor coming over to do

00:55:45.770 --> 00:55:48.450
some demolition in the house,
everybody takes off their

00:55:48.450 --> 00:55:53.830
jackets, their neckties, the
shirts they put on, their

00:55:53.830 --> 00:55:55.962
turtleneck sweaters.

00:55:55.962 --> 00:56:02.570
They don't want to look wrong
when these working men arrive.

00:56:02.570 --> 00:56:04.230
Of course, the working men say,
oh, these poor people,

00:56:04.230 --> 00:56:06.460
they're reduced to rags.

00:56:06.460 --> 00:56:10.310
[LAUGHTER]

00:56:10.310 --> 00:56:11.980
TOM WOLFE: Thomas Jefferson
took care of class in this

00:56:11.980 --> 00:56:14.380
country, and it has
never reappeared.

00:56:14.380 --> 00:56:19.110
When America was finally
recognized by England, and the

00:56:19.110 --> 00:56:24.330
British ambassador arrives for
this historic meeting in the

00:56:24.330 --> 00:56:29.060
White House, he's wearing some
kind of military cap from god

00:56:29.060 --> 00:56:29.540
knows when.

00:56:29.540 --> 00:56:31.565
He has a ceremonial sword.

00:56:31.565 --> 00:56:34.630
It's about this long,
but it's a sword.

00:56:34.630 --> 00:56:36.260
All sorts of trappings.

00:56:36.260 --> 00:56:39.450
Jefferson meets him in
his bedroom slippers.

00:56:39.450 --> 00:56:40.250
It wasn't the bedroom.

00:56:40.250 --> 00:56:43.460
But he comes out in his bedroom
slippers to the great

00:56:43.460 --> 00:56:45.862
portico as you go in
the White House.

00:56:45.862 --> 00:56:50.085
And dinner, here's the British
ambassador and his wife, and

00:56:50.085 --> 00:56:54.540
all these dignitaries, mostly
American, who are there.

00:56:54.540 --> 00:56:55.840
And he says, well,
this dinner's

00:56:55.840 --> 00:56:59.050
going to be pell mell.

00:56:59.050 --> 00:57:01.170
They say, what do you
mean, pell mell?

00:57:01.170 --> 00:57:03.650
He said, well, if you see a seat
you like, and you're near

00:57:03.650 --> 00:57:07.020
it, take it.

00:57:07.020 --> 00:57:09.750
And they found that all the
tables were round so that

00:57:09.750 --> 00:57:11.700
there was no head
of the table.

00:57:11.700 --> 00:57:15.940
This was all thought
out by Jefferson.

00:57:15.940 --> 00:57:20.940
And the only person who's taken
to a seat, and assigned

00:57:20.940 --> 00:57:23.520
seat, was the wife
of ambassador.

00:57:23.520 --> 00:57:27.190
And Jefferson seated
her next to him.

00:57:27.190 --> 00:57:28.950
Everybody else, including
the ambassador, had

00:57:28.950 --> 00:57:30.800
to rush to a seat.

00:57:30.800 --> 00:57:33.400
And if it was occupied,
well, it was too bad.

00:57:33.400 --> 00:57:37.016
It was this pell mell system.

00:57:37.016 --> 00:57:42.820
And these things were all done
by Jefferson to say, that old

00:57:42.820 --> 00:57:45.070
stuff is over.

00:57:45.070 --> 00:57:46.640
We are not in Europe.

00:57:46.640 --> 00:57:50.600
He made John Marshall, the Chief
Justice of the United

00:57:50.600 --> 00:57:52.950
States take the ribbons--

00:57:52.950 --> 00:57:56.440
he had noticed in Europe, the
Chief Judge would often have

00:57:56.440 --> 00:58:01.020
these golden ribbons across
the black robe--

00:58:01.020 --> 00:58:03.760
he made Marshall take his off.

00:58:03.760 --> 00:58:06.050
We're not going to
have that stuff.

00:58:06.050 --> 00:58:08.860
RICK KLEFFEL: What we are
going to have is this.

00:58:08.860 --> 00:58:13.750
An America that has gone
"Back to Blood," and

00:58:13.750 --> 00:58:16.160
YouTube, as it were.

00:58:16.160 --> 00:58:19.830
TOM WOLFE: I explained that I
don't mind horror fiction when

00:58:19.830 --> 00:58:20.790
people are thinking
of buying my book.

00:58:20.790 --> 00:58:23.610
But it's not wet blood.

00:58:23.610 --> 00:58:25.990
It's bloodlines.

00:58:25.990 --> 00:58:26.520
RICK KLEFFEL: Bloodlines.

00:58:26.520 --> 00:58:28.215
TOM WOLFE: I should
warn you of that.

00:58:31.050 --> 00:58:32.620
RICK KLEFFEL: Ladies and
gentlemen, we have been graced

00:58:32.620 --> 00:58:34.330
to have with us Tom Wolfe.

00:58:34.330 --> 00:58:36.840
He is the author of "The
Electric Kool-Aid Acid Test,"

00:58:36.840 --> 00:58:39.625
"The Right Stuff," and his
newest novel is "Back to

00:58:39.625 --> 00:58:40.840
Blood." Thank you
for joining me.

00:58:40.840 --> 00:58:42.080
And thank you for
joining me, Tom.

00:58:42.080 --> 00:58:43.080
It was a pleasure.

00:58:43.080 --> 00:58:43.800
TOM WOLFE: Thanks.

